{{Infobox military conflict |conflict= 1972 Israeli air raid in Syria and Lebanon |partof=the [[Operation Wrath of God]] |image= |caption= |date=September 8, 1972 |place=[[Palestine refugee camps|Palestinian refugee camps in Syria and southern Lebanon]] |[[casus belli]]=[[Munich massacre]] |result=[[Israel Air Force]] destroyed [[Palestinian fedayeen|fedayeen]] training camps |combatant1={{flagicon|Israel}} [[Israel]] |combatant2= {{flagicon|Palestine}} [[Palestine Liberation Organization|PLO]] |commander1= |commander2= |strength1= |strength2= |casualties1=None |casualties2=65-200 killed }} {{Campaignbox Palestinian insurgency in South Lebanon}} {{Campaignbox Wrath of God}} On 8 September, Israeli planes bombed ten [[Palestine Liberation Organization|PLO]] bases in [[Syria]] and [[Lebanon]] as a response to the [[Munich massacre]]. Estimates of the number of casualties vary widely. According to [[Simon Reeve]], 200 people with no relation to the massacre were killed, including women and children.<ref>[http://books.google.dk/books?id=BcAsBHZ4DLwC&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false One day in September: the full story of the 1972 Munich Olympics massacre]</ref><ref>http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=799&dat=19720908&id=XRQLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8lEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7382,4309634</ref><ref>http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qFQqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SFMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7375,2140792&hl=en</ref>
